full_text.11:
Mistakes in a solo business can be catastrophic.

I'm talking full-blown bankruptcy, lawsuits, and outright humiliation catastrophic.

These are not factors when you take the time to actually learn how to play the game.

So, now what?
full_text.12:
These provide a foundation so you can build the necessary fundamental skills AND the tangential skills that you had no idea existed.

By removing the pressure of clients with expectations (rightly so if they're paying you), you can learn in an environment that allows mistakes.
full_text.13:
What you're really asking:

"How do I gain experience sufficient enough to run my own business?"

You have 3 primary options:

1. Get a job and learn
2. Apprentice under a pro
3. Provide services for free (or very little) to practice

ALL of these requires time and patience.
full_text.14:
And here's the biggest hurdle for someone starting out:

The only way to truly learn all the skills sufficient for running your own business is to ACTUALLY DO THEM. 

"But, how can I do them if I can't get any clients?"

You're not going to like the answer...
full_text.15:
The COMMODITY of taking photos is necessary to solve the overall problem.

But, it's not sufficient.

The same lesson applies to any profession.

Inexperienced people get this wrong all the time. 

They only recognize the commodity itself, and believe they, too, can deliver it.
full_text.16:
For example:

A wedding photographer is paid to:

- Capture every magic moment
- Stay out of the way of the moment
- Manage the mother-in-law
- Ramp up the energy of the subjects
- Fully-understand the order of events
- Make billing easy

And, yes, to actually take the photos.
full_text.17:
They're failing to recognize why people part with their hard-earned money.

They pay you when you solve a problem.

"Needing pretty pictures" is PART of a problem, but it's not the entire problem.

Fixating on just the skill set blinds you to what you're actually paid to do.
